opportunities for Aboriginal peoples, traditional occupations and Native languages suffered. Focusing on the final years of the Soviet Union, the authors describe the efforts of Aboriginal political activists to address the problem of protecting Aboriginal rights in nations with large, non-Aboriginal majorities and explore whether protection of traditional cultures excludes participation in the larger society. In addressing these universal issues, When the North Was Red is relevant to all nations where Native peoples co-exist with non-Aboriginal majorities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutochtonesxÉducationxHistoirexRussiexSibérie. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationxHistoryxRussia (Federation)xSiberia. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzRussia (Federation)zSiberiaxHistory. 0aÉducationxPolitique gouvernementalexHistoirexURSSxRussia (Federation)xSiberiaxSibérie (Russie)xRelations interethniques. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBartels, Alice L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773565579?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773565579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773565579/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles